
Routing
🎯 Objective

Understand what routing is, how routers work, the different types of routing, routing tables, routing protocols, and how Linux systems make routing decisions.

📖 What is Routing?

Routing is the process of forwarding data packets from one network to another using a router.

When a device wants to communicate with another device on a different network, the router determines the best path and forwards the packet.

Example

Your laptop is on:

192.168.1.10

A web server is on:

142.250.183.206

Since these devices are on different networks, the data passes through one or more routers before reaching the destination.

Why Do We Need Routing?

Without routing:

Devices could communicate only within the same network.
Internet communication would not be possible.
Large enterprise networks could not connect different offices.

Routing allows communication between:

Home networks
Office networks
Data centers
Cloud networks (AWS, Azure, GCP)
The Internet


