What is a Router?

A router is a networking device that connects different networks and forwards packets based on IP addresses.

Functions of a router:

Connects multiple networks
Chooses the best path
Forwards packets
Maintains a routing table
Can perform NAT, DHCP, and firewall functions
Routing Table

A routing table contains information about:

Destination network
Gateway (Next Hop)
Network interface
Route metric

Example:

Destination        Gateway         Interface
0.0.0.0/0          192.168.1.1     eth0
192.168.1.0/24     Direct          eth0
10.0.0.0/24        192.168.2.1     eth1
Types of Routing
1. Static Routing

Routes are manually configured.

Advantages
Easy for small networks
Predictable
Low resource usage
Disadvantages
Manual updates
Not scalable
2. Dynamic Routing

Routers automatically learn routes using routing protocols.

Examples:

RIP
OSPF
EIGRP
BGP
Advantages
Automatically adapts to network changes
Scalable
Suitable for large networks
Disadvantages
More CPU and memory usage
More complex to configure


Static vs Dynamic Routing
| Feature       | Static Routing | Dynamic Routing |
| ------------- | -------------- | --------------- |
| Configuration | Manual         | Automatic       |
| Best For      | Small Networks | Large Networks  |
| Maintenance   | High           | Low             |
| Scalability   | Limited        | Excellent       |
| Updates       | Manual         | Automatic       |
| Complexity    | Low            | Higher          |



Default Gateway

The Default Gateway is the router that forwards packets when the destination network is not directly connected.

Example:

Laptop

IP Address:
192.168.1.10

Gateway:
192.168.1.1

When you access a website, your laptop sends the packet to 192.168.1.1, and the router forwards it toward the destination.

Linux Commands
Display Routing Table
ip route
Display IP Address
ip addr
Show Network Interfaces
ip link
Display Active Connections
ss -tun
Trace Packet Path
traceroute google.com

If traceroute is not installed:

sudo apt install traceroute

Routing Protocols
| Protocol | Full Form                                  | Use Case                               |
| -------- | ------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------- |
| RIP      | Routing Information Protocol               | Small networks                         |
| OSPF     | Open Shortest Path First                   | Enterprise networks                    |
| EIGRP    | Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol | Cisco environments                     |
| BGP      | Border Gateway Protocol                    | Internet routing between organizations |

AWS Example

In AWS, Route Tables determine where traffic goes.

Example:

VPC
│
├── Public Route Table
│     └── 0.0.0.0/0 → Internet Gateway
│
└── Private Route Table
      └── 0.0.0.0/0 → NAT Gateway

This is one of the most common networking configurations you'll create in AWS.

